\code{\link[=gdpins_go_offline]{gdpins_go_offline()}}, the prune verbs — plus
\code{\link[=gdpins_board_connect]{gdpins_board_connect()}}, which exists to force it deliberately.

\code{\link[=print]{print()}}, \code{\link[=format]{format()}}, and \code{\link[=summary]{summary()}} do \strong{not} force: they describe the
board from its declared config. Nor do the plain metadata fields (\code{name},
\code{config}, \code{versioned}, \code{drive_path}, \code{cache_dir}, \code{local_dir}, \code{adapter}).
}

\section{Consequences}{

Errors move. A mistyped \code{drive_path}, a missing folder with \code{create = FALSE}, or the \code{create = NA} interactive prompt used to fire at
\code{gdpins_init_board()}; they now fire at first use. Call
\code{\link[=gdpins_board_connect]{gdpins_board_connect()}} right after init to get the old timing back, or
pass \code{lazy = FALSE}.

Connection state is shared, not copied. \code{b2 <- board} gives two handles onto
one connection: forcing either resolves both. This is deliberate — it stops
a board passed to a function from reconnecting inside it.

If \code{.build_board()} fails, the board stays unresolved and the next access
retries. A transient network failure does not permanently poison the board.
}

\section{Disabling}{

Set \code{options(gdpins.lazy_boards = FALSE)} to make every
\code{gdpins_init_board()} call eager, or pass \code{lazy = FALSE} per board. An
explicit \code{lazy} argument always beats the option.
}

